 "modules": [
  {
   "title": "Module 1 · Definition",
   "html": "<p>A logarithm answers the question: <i>to what power must the base be raised to get this number?</i></p>$$\\log_b N = x \\iff b^x = N$$<p>Common logarithms use base 10. We write $\\log N$ meaning $\\log_{10} N$.</p><p><b>Laws of logarithms</b></p><ol><li>$\\log(MN)=\\log M+\\log N$</li><li>$\\log(M/N)=\\log M-\\log N$</li><li>$\\log(M^k)=k\\log M$</li><li>$\\log_b b = 1$, $\\log_b 1 = 0$</li></ol>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Evaluate $\\log_2 32$.",
     "a": "$32 = 2^5$, so $\\log_2 32 = 5$."
    },
    {
     "q": "Express $\\log 6$ in terms of $\\log 2$ and $\\log 3$.",
     "a": "$\\log 6 = \\log(2\\cdot 3) = \\log 2 + \\log 3$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 2 · Characteristic and Mantissa",
   "html": "<p>For $N>1$, $\\log_{10} N$ has two parts:</p><ul><li>The <b>characteristic</b> — the integer part — equals (number of digits before the decimal point) $-1$.</li><li>The <b>mantissa</b> — the decimal part — is read from the log table.</li></ul><p>Example: $\\log 350$ has characteristic $2$ (three digits), mantissa $0.5441$, so $\\log 350 \\approx 2.5441$.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "State the characteristic of $\\log 4560$.",
     "a": "$4560$ has 4 digits, so the characteristic is $4-1 = 3$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 3 · Using Log Tables",
   "html": "<p>To compute products, quotients, powers and roots quickly:</p>$$\\log(MN)=\\log M+\\log N,\\quad \\log(M/N)=\\log M-\\log N$$$$\\log(M^k)=k\\log M,\\quad \\log(\\sqrt[n]{M})=\\tfrac{1}{n}\\log M$$<p>Take logs, add/subtract/multiply, then use the antilog table to convert back.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Use logs to evaluate $23.4 \\times 5.62$.",
     "a": "$\\log 23.4 \\approx 1.3692$; $\\log 5.62 \\approx 0.7497$. Sum $= 2.1189$. Antilog $= 131.5$."
    }
   ]
  }
 ],
